{"_id":"aFRNiBtY6fbXqZ0I","name":"Patron Taint: Sezrekan","permission":{"default":0,"wWErSsSXezizF0nw":3},"folder":"","flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"JournalEntry.sDlD3Dndt3InNrKF"}},"content":"<p>pg. 337</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>@Compendium[dcc-core-book.dcc-core-spell-effect-tables.bsWbWYOywjkoLrgP]{Patron Taint: Sezrekan}</p>\n<table style=\"width: 99.1453%; height: 554px;\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr style=\"height: 17px;\">\n<td style=\"width: 7.90386%; height: 17px;\" align=\"left\" height=\"17\"><strong>Roll</strong></td>\n<td style=\"width: 91.8088%; height: 17px;\" align=\"left\"><strong>Result</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height: 119px;\">\n<td style=\"width: 7.90386%; height: 119px;\" align=\"left\" height=\"17\">1-1</td>\n<td style=\"width: 91.8088%; height: 119px;\" align=\"left\">Incited to madness and brimming with occult knowledge, the caster spends his next action carving a third eye into his forehead (inflicting [[/roll 1d3]] points of damage in the process). Upon return to civilization, the caster seeks out a tattooist who inks a third eye on the caster&rsquo;s forehead using exotic inks costing no less than [[/roll 1d5]] x 100 gp. If the Result is rolled a second time, the caster insists on wearing a blindfold for the next [[/roll 1d4]] days, in the earnest hope of awakening his third eye. If the result is rolled a third time, the caster stabs a dagger into each of his real eyes, blinding himself. (There is a 3% chance, per level, that the self-mutilation brings the PC&rsquo;s third eye to life.)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height: 119px;\">\n<td style=\"width: 7.90386%; height: 119px;\" align=\"left\" height=\"17\">2-2</td>\n<td style=\"width: 91.8088%; height: 119px;\" align=\"left\">Dazzled by his new insight into the terrifying nature of the multiverse, the caster is spurred into offering up sacrifices in thanks to the Old Master. The caster is driven to enact the ritual as soon as it is reasonably safe, though the caster&rsquo;s threat assessment may not agree with that of his peers. In a ritual lasting 1 turn, the caster offers up wealth totaling at least [[/roll 1d5]] x 100 gp in honor of Sezrekan. All the items are consumed in searing blue flames, and there is a 3% chance that Sezrekan honors the sacrifice with a +1 bonus to the caster&rsquo;s next spell check. If the Result is rolled a second time, the caster must sacrifice a magic item</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height: 102px;\">\n<td style=\"width: 7.90386%; height: 102px;\" align=\"left\" height=\"17\">3-3</td>\n<td style=\"width: 91.8088%; height: 102px;\" align=\"left\">In a passing moment of d&eacute;j&agrave; vu, the caster realizes that Sezrekan demands his service. Subject to the judge&rsquo;s discretion, the caster must adventure to retrieve an occult item or lost relic for the Old Master, located within [[/roll 1d4]] days travel. The caster has a clear vision of the item, but only a rough sense of its location and wards. If the Result is rolled a second time, the item is well warded and some [[/roll 1d4]] weeks distant. If the result is rolled a third time, the item is guarded by ancient wards, traps, and fiends, requiring [[/roll 1d4]] months of dangerous travel.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height: 102px;\">\n<td style=\"width: 7.90386%; height: 102px;\" align=\"left\" height=\"17\">4-4</td>\n<td style=\"width: 91.8088%; height: 102px;\" align=\"left\">In a lucid dream of mighty Sezrekan, the caster realizes his own spells are terribly flawed and dependent on the aid of outsiders. Forsaking their influence, the caster gives up a known first level spell, vowing to never cast it again. (If, later, the caster discovers another spell of the same level, it can take the place of the original spell among the caster&rsquo;s known spells.) If the Result is rolled a second time, the caster must surrender a second level spell. If the result is rolled a third time, the caster must surrender a third level spell. Should the caster refuse to give up any of the spells, he forsakes Sezrekan as his patron.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height: 85px;\">\n<td style=\"width: 7.90386%; height: 85px;\" align=\"left\" height=\"17\">5-5</td>\n<td style=\"width: 91.8088%; height: 85px;\" align=\"left\">The daunting scope of the caster&rsquo;s knowledge induces a creeping madness that begins to seep into his everyday life. The caster must declare a common substance (iron, water, steel, cotton, gold, silver, silk, wood, leather, velum, meat, etc.) and declare it taboo. Henceforth, the caster makes every effort to avoid contact with the taboo substance. If the Result is rolled a second time, the caster must choose a second taboo substance. If the result is rolled a second time, the caster must choose a second taboo; furthermore, contact with the forbidden substances causes searing burns that inflict 1 hp of damage per round of contact. If the result is rolled a third time, the caster must pick a third taboo, and contact inflicts [[/roll 1d4]] hp of damage per round of contact.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style=\"height: 10px;\">\n<td style=\"width: 7.90386%; height: 10px;\" align=\"left\" height=\"17\">6-6</td>\n<td style=\"width: 91.8088%; height: 10px;\" align=\"left\">The caster is caught up in a dream world of hallucinations for the next [[/roll 1d5]] rounds, as a spectral image of Sezrekan strides through his vision. The caster can still interact with the real world, but if he chooses to ignore his surroundings and watch only the Old Master, he gleans hints and indications of Sezrekan&rsquo;s dweomercaft mastery. If the caster spends the next [[/roll 1d4]] days in solitary research, he is able to learn a new spell of his choosing. Failing to immediately retire to study causes the insights to be lost, like the fading memory of a dream. This Result can be rolled up to three times.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><br /><br /></p>"}
